{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39530921-0543-422e-89b1-1c46d949b2d9","content":"Given it's mid-2026, you're most likely on **.NET 9 (or newer)**, which **requires JDK 21** — JDK 17 is no longer sufficient.\n\nStarting with .NET 9, the Android workload bumped its minimum Java requirement from 17 to **21**.\n\n### Fix\n\nInstall JDK 21 and update `JAVA_HOME`:\n\n```bash\n# Option A: Microsoft OpenJDK (recommended for MAUI)\nbrew install --cask microsoft-openjdk@21\n\nexport JAVA_HOME=\"/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-21.jdk/Contents/Home\"\n\n# Option B: Adoptium Temurin 21\nbrew install --cask temurin@21\n\nexport JAVA_HOME=$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 21)\n```\n\nAdd the `export` line to your `~/.zshrc` (or `~/.bash_profile`) to persist it, then rebuild.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"61427a07-3829-4cfd-8917-2b72b551dd12","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android build issues related to Java:\n\n1. .NET MAUI (especially newer versions like .NET 8+) requires JDK 17, which they have.\n2. However, a very common issue on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is that JAVA_HOME needs to point to the correct path. On macOS, Adoptium installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home/`.\n\n\n3. There's also potential conflict between the JDK that ships with .NET MAUI/Android SDK and the system JAVA_HOME setting, since the build system might reference `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` instead.\n4. The actual error often stems from a JDK version mismatch or the Android SDK's build tools not finding the right `javac` version.\n\nLet me consider what specific error they're encountering—they mentioned Temurin 17.0.12+7, which should be compatible, but there might be a path resolution issue on macOS that's preventing the build system from locating the JDK properly. On macOS, the path needs to include `.../Contents/Home` rather than stopping at the `.jdk` directory. The real issue is likely that setting JAVA_HOME overrides the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the Android workload, which can cause incompatibilities. The best approach is either sticking with the workload's built-in JDK or ensuring any custom JDK is properly compatible with the Android Gradle Plugin version being used. The most likely culprit is that .NET 9 MAUI actually requires JDK 21, not JDK 17—so if they upgraded to .NET 9, their Temurin 17 setup would fail the build with a version mismatch error. So .NET 9 requires JDK 21 for the Android workload—that's the breaking change here. The user has Temurin 17, which won't satisfy that requirement. They need to install JDK 21 and update their JAVA_HOME environment variable to point to it.","outputTokens":1712,"requestId":"142A:1BD824:A3EBF5:B9DAE1:6A03CC46"},"id":"c5da4d0b-0d99-44cc-a87d-350608bf5174","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:57:13.840Z","parentId":"e4270225-288d-484d-905f-d6439ed219d8"}
